Pour the @water for the rice{300%ml} into a #saucepan{} and bring to the boil. When
boiling, add @salt{0.25%tsp}, stir in the @Jasmine Rice{150%g}, lower the heat to
medium and pop a lid on the pan. Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the
pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes}
or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Using a #peeler{}, peel the @Mango{½}(peeled) then stand it upright on your
#chopping board{}. Slice down either side of the stone to give you 2 'cheeks'.
Slice any remaining flesh from the stone, then chop the mango into 1cm pieces.
Discard the stone and pop the flesh into a #medium bowl{}. Peel the
@Kiwi{1}(peeled) and chop into 1cm pieces and pop into the bowl with the mango.

Trim the @Spring Onion{2}(trimmed) then slice thinly. Halve the @Red Chilli{½},
de-seed then finely chop. Roughly chop the @Coriander{1}(chopped roughly, stalks and
all). Add the spring onion coriander and as much chilli as you dare to the salsa
and give it a good stir. Zest and halve the @Lime{1}. Keep the zest to one side.
Squeeze the lime juice into a #bowl{}, add the @Soy Sauce{25%ml} and
@Sesame Oil{12%ml} and mix well. Halve the @Pak Choi{2} lengthways.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #large frying pan{} over medium-high heat. Once hot,
lay in the bok choy, cut-side down. Season with @salt{} and a grind of
@black pepper{}. Cook for ~{2%minutes}, then turn over and cook for another
~{2%minutes} on the other side. The bok choy should be slightly browned and
charred. Add a splash of @water{} and pop a #lid{} (or some #foil{}) on the pan and
leave to steam for another ~{3%minutes}. Set the bok choy aside and cover with
foil to keep warm but don't wash up the pan!

When the rice is nearly ready, wipe out the #frying pan{} then return to medium
high heat with a drizzle of @oil{}. Add the @Sea Bream Fillets{2} to the pan skin
side down, season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and cook until the skin is golden
brown, ~{2-3%minutes}, then turn over and cook for a further ~{2%minutes}.

> Don't move the fish while it's cooking skin side down or you won't get a crispy
> skin! IMPORTANT: The fish is cooked when opaque in the middle.

While the fish cooks, pour the dressing into the mango bowl and mix well to coat.
Add the lime zest to the rice and carefully stir through with a #fork{}. Divide
the rice between plates then top with the sea bream and serve with the mango and
kiwi salsa and the charred bok choy alongside. Enjoy!